Thanks, @azadgupta1. The integration point you're targeting is correct. When axios falls back to `http.globalAgent` and Node has `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1`, having axios *also* apply env-derived proxy resolution causes double-proxying, and bypassing axios's logic in that case is the correct approach.

The biggest thing I'd want to nail down before this lands is the Node version threshold. As far as I can tell, `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY` shipped in **Node 24.0.0** (April 2025), not 22.11. Before merging I'd want a specific Node PR or release-notes link confirming a backport to a 22.x LTS line, because silently disabling axios proxy handling on Node 22.11+ when Node *isn't* actually doing the env work would mean some users' proxies just stop applying, with no signal. If 24.0.0 turns out to be the right floor, the comparator should be `major >= 24`.

The other correctness gap is that the early return is too aggressive. It sits at the top of `setProxy`, before the block that consumes user-supplied `configProxy`, so:

```js
axios.get('https://api.example.com', {
  proxy: { host: '10.0.0.1', port: 3128 }
});

```

With `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` in the environment, it now silently ignores the explicit proxy option and routes through Node's `globalAgent` instead. Same problem with custom `agents: NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY` only applies when Node uses `http.globalAgent` or `fetch`, so if the user has config.httpAgent / config.httpsAgent set, nobody ends up applying a proxy. The condition needs to be tightened on both axes:

```js
const hasCustomAgent = !!(config.httpAgent || config.httpsAgent);
if (!configProxy && !hasCustomAgent && process.env.NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY === '1' && nodeSupportsNativeProxy) {
  return;
}
```

Two smaller notes. The PR description promises `semver.gte(process.versions.node, '22.11.0')`, but the implementation uses `String#split('.').map(Number)` with a manual major/minor compare that drops prerelease suffixes silently and only compares two components. Axios doesn't depend on semver, so importing it would add a runtime dep, but the parser should match the precision the threshold actually needs. And the redirect-time Proxy-Authorization strip lives inside `setProxy()` (the `options.beforeRedirects.proxy = …` registration at the bottom), so the early return also skips that, probably fine when Node is handling auth, but worth a test confirming Proxy-Authorization doesn't leak across a 30x redirect to an off-proxy host with `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` set.

Also needs tests covering the env/version branches (stubbing process.env and process.versions.node), trailing whitespace cleanup on the line after the if block, and a rebase against v1.x.

