Thanks for picking this up — `signal.reason` propagation has been on the wishlist and the overall shape here is right. Three things to sort before it lands.

**The new tests aren't actually running.** They target `test/specs/cancel.spec.js` and `test/unit/adapters/http.js`, both deleted in commit `a7f41f5` when the suite migrated to vitest. The current home is `tests/unit/**/*.test.js` — the cancel test belongs in `tests/unit/cancel/canceledError.test.js`, the http one in `tests/unit/adapters/http.test.js`. CI is green because vitest isn't picking these files up, not because they pass.

**The backwards-compat claim isn't accurate.** The PR body says "only affects aborts where AbortSignal.reason exists", but per spec `signal.reason` is *always* defined once aborted — `controller.abort()` with no argument sets it to `DOMException('signal is aborted without reason', 'AbortError')`. Walk that through `dispatchRequest.js`: `reason instanceof Error` is true, so `error.message` flips from the current `"canceled"` to `"signal is aborted without reason"`. Anyone matching on the message string sees a regression.

The fix is a one-liner — detect the spec-default AbortError and keep the existing message:

```js
if (reason && reason.name === 'AbortError' && reason instanceof DOMException) {
  return new CanceledError(null, config, request); // preserve "canceled"
}
```

**Fetch is left out.** `lib/adapters/fetch.js:412-420` only honors `reason instanceof AxiosError`. After this PR, http and xhr propagate string and plain-`Error` reasons but fetch doesn't — same abort, different `error.message` depending on which adapter answered. Adapter parity is the whole reason axios has the abstraction; fetch needs to come along.

A few code-shape notes:

The "is it cancel? is it Error? else stringify?" ladder is duplicated across `dispatchRequest`, `http`, and `xhr`. Worth lifting into a static factory next to the existing `AxiosError.from`:

```js
// lib/cancel/CanceledError.js
static from(reason, config, request) {
  if (reason && reason.__CANCEL__) return reason;
  if (reason && reason.name === 'AbortError' && reason instanceof DOMException) {
    return new CanceledError(null, config, request);
  }
  const message = reason instanceof Error ? reason.message
                : reason == null ? null
                : String(reason);
  const error = new CanceledError(message, config, request);
  if (reason instanceof Error) error.cause = reason;
  return error;
}
```

Each adapter becomes `CanceledError.from(reason, config, req)`, and fetch picks up the same helper instead of carrying its own variant.

The IIFE inside `abortEmitter.emit('abort', ...)` in `http.js` is rough to read at a glance — with the helper it just goes away, but flagging in case the helper approach isn't where you want to go.

Edge case worth a test: `controller.abort({ kind: 'replaced' })` currently lands as `error.message === '[object Object]'`. The `String(reason)` branch in the helper above fixes it.

Coverage gaps to fill once the test files are at the right paths: nothing asserts `.cause` propagation for an `Error` reason (the more interesting half of the feature), there's no test for `controller.abort()` with no argument (the regression case above), and the fetch adapter and the synchronous `dispatchRequest` path (signal already aborted before the adapter runs) aren't exercised at all.

Happy to take another pass once the helper is in place and the tests are running where vitest can find them.

