Thanks for the patch — the diagnosis is correct and the fix is the right shape.

The descriptor shape you've landed on is also slightly better than the `78b290c` original adding `writable: true` aligns it with what V8/ECMA-262 does for `new Error('msg', { cause: x }) ([[Writable]]: true, [[Enumerable]]: false, [[Configurable]]: true)`. Good call.

Two follow-ups before this is complete.

**Two more leak sites in lib/adapters/fetch.js need the same treatment.**

`lib/adapters/fetch.js:419: err !== canceledError && (canceledError.cause = err);`
`lib/adapters/fetch.js:433: cause: err.cause || err,    // inside Object.assign(new AxiosError(...), { cause: ... })`

Both assign cause enumerably and have the same JSON.stringify failure for the same reasons. Anyone hitting #7205 on the http adapter will file the same issue against fetch unless these are addressed too.

Since the pattern now repeats three times, cleanest is a small helper next to AxiosError:

```js
// lib/core/AxiosError.js
function setCause(error, cause) {
  Object.defineProperty(error, 'cause', {
    value: cause,
    configurable: true,
    writable: true,
  });
}
```

AxiosError.from then becomes:

`setCause(axiosError, error);`

And the two fetch sites:

```js
// fetch.js:419
err !== canceledError && setCause(canceledError, err);

// fetch.js:433 — split the Object.assign so setCause owns the cause
const networkError = new AxiosError(
  'Network Error',
  AxiosError.ERR_NETWORK,
  config,
  request,
  err && err.response
);
setCause(networkError, err.cause || err);
throw networkError;
```

The current `Object.assign(new AxiosError(...), { cause: ... })` form is what makes that site enumerable; extracting cause out of the assign lets `setCause` do the right thing.

A bigger-but-cleaner option for later: extend AxiosError's constructor to accept cause and forward to `super(message, { cause })`. The native Error constructor already sets it non-enumerable per spec, and the helper goes away entirely. Probably a separate PR — flagging in case it's of interest.

**Lock it in with tests. Two cases in tests/unit/core/AxiosError.test.js:**

```js
it('JSON.stringify works when the original error has circular references', () => {
  const sock = {};
  sock.self = sock;
  const original = Object.assign(new Error('boom'), { socket: sock });
  const axiosError = AxiosError.from(original, 'ENETWORK', {});
  expect(() => JSON.stringify(axiosError)).not.toThrow();
});

it('cause is non-enumerable and matches native Error.cause shape', () => {
  const axiosError = AxiosError.from(new Error('x'), 'E', {});
  const desc = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(axiosError, 'cause');
  expect(desc.enumerable).toBe(false);
  expect(desc.configurable).toBe(true);
  expect(desc.writable).toBe(true);
});
```

The first pins the bug. The second pins the descriptor shape so the next refactor that touches this code doesn't silently flatten it again, which is exactly how the regression got in the first place.

Thanks for picking this up — #6511 has been sitting open a while, and the diagnosis here is exactly right. `Object.assign(axiosError, customProps)` at the top of `AxiosError.from` makes the props enumerable own properties, but `toJSON()` returns a hand-rolled shape that ignores them. Pino and friends call `toJSON()` and lose every `traceId`/`requestId` the caller attached. Spreading enumerable own props is the right fix, and putting the spread *before* the standard fields is the right call — canonical fields win on collision, so a user accidentally passing `customProps: { message: 'override' }` can't corrupt the canonical shape.

